```python
class Stack:
    def __init__(self):
        self.items = []

    def push(self, item):
        self.items.append(item)

    def pop(self):
        if not self.is_empty():
            return self.items.pop()
        else:
            raise Exception("Stack is empty")

    def peek(self):
        if not self.is_empty():
            return self.items[-1]
        else:
            raise Exception("Stack is empty")

    def is_empty(self):
        return len(self.items) == 0

class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.in_stack = Stack()
        self.out_stack = Stack()

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.in_stack.push(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if self.out_stack.isEmpty():
            while not self.in_stack.isEmpty():
                self.out_stack.push(self.in_stack.pop())

            return self.out_stack.pop()
        else:
            return self.out_stack.pop()

    def front(self):
        if not self.out_stack.isEmpty():
            return self.out_stack.peek()
        else:
            raise Exception("Queue is empty")

    def back(self):
        if not self.in_stack.isEmpty():
            return self.in_stack.peek()
        else:
            raise Exception("Queue is empty")

    def is_full(self):
        return False # This implementation assumes that there is no upper limit to the size of the queue.

    def is_empty(self):
        return self.in_stack.isEmpty() and self.out_stack.isEmpty()

# Example usage:
q = Queue()

print(q.enqueue(5))
print(q.dequeue())
print(q.front())
print(q.back())
```

This implementation uses two `Stack` objects - one for incoming elements (the "in" stack), and another for outgoing elements (the "out" stack). When an element is added with `enqueue`, it gets pushed onto the "in" stack. If the "out" stack is empty, then when the next dequeue operation is performed, all elements from the "in" stack get popped into the "out" stack until the first element can be returned as the head of the queue. Afterward, subsequent dequeue operations just pop elements off the "out" stack. The `front` method checks the top element of the "out" stack, which is the last-in element in the queue. Similarly, the `back` method checks the last element of the "in" stack, which is the first-in element in the queue. Finally, the `is_full` method is not implemented because this implementation assumes that there is no upper limit to the size of the queue. Note that in order for the queue to function properly, we assume that we never have any more than O(n) operations on the queue at once.
